         <abstract>
            <p>Public debt is not an unmitigated good nor an unmitigated evil. In depressions, we need a compensatory fiscal policy to promote stability. A developmental fiscal program in which we engage in broad basic developmental public investment, which in turn opens private investment outlets, is also needed. A long-range debt increase that might arise therefrom may be justified. It provides a larger money supply. The nest-egg of a mass holding of bonds is a certain safeguard against very serious depression. When taxes are levied now to pay interest on bonds, the money is paid back to citizens and institutions, and they in turn spend for consumption or investment. The all-important question is how to keep income at the full employment level. If this is done we shall have a national income high enough to pay taxes.</p>
